/**
 Express.js Routing â€“ app.use() vs app.get()/post()/put()/delete()

ðŸ”¹ Express.js route checking rule (IMPORTANT)
- Express.js routes ko top to bottom check karta hai
- Jo route sabse pehle match ho jata hai, wahi execute hota hai
- Jaise hi res.send() / res.json() / res.sendFile() call hota hai
  ðŸ‘‰ response close ho jata hai
  ðŸ‘‰ aage ke routes check nahi hote

ðŸ”¹ app.use() ka rule (Middleware rule)

Syntax:
app.use(path, callback)

Rules:
- Exact path match zaroori nahi hota
- HTTP method ka koi role nahi hota
- Koi bhi HTTP method ho sakta hai (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, etc.)
- Path prefix match hota hai

Matlab:
Agar user ka request URL, app.use() ke path se start hota hai,
to app.use() execute ho jayega

Example:
app.use("/contact", handler);

Ye sab match karega:
- /contact
- /contact/help
- /contact/address

Ye match nahi karega:
- /about
- /login

ðŸ”¹ app.get() / app.post() / app.put() / app.delete() ka rule

Rules:
- HTTP method exact match hona chahiye
- Path exact match hona chahiye
- Prefix match nahi hota

Example:
app.get("/about", handler);

Match karega:
- GET /about

Match nahi karega:
- POST /about
- GET /about/us

ðŸ”¹ Summary table (Quick Revision)

Feature                     | app.use()        | app.get()/post()/put()/delete()
--------------------------- | ---------------- | ------------------------------
HTTP Method                 | Any              | Exact
Path matching               | Prefix           | Exact
Middleware ke liye          | Best             | Not recommended
Direct page/API ke liye     | Risky            | Safe
Route order important       | Yes              | Yes

 Dry Run Example â€“ Case 1

import express from "express";
const app = express();

app.use("/about/address", (req, res) => {
  res.send("app.use() method called");
});

app.get("/address/pincode", (req, res) => {
  res.send("app.get() method called");
});

Request:
GET /address/pincode

Execution flow:
1) Express top se route check karega
2) app.use("/about/address") milega
3) app.use() har method ke liye valid hota hai
4) Path ka last meaningful part = address
5) User ka URL address se start ho raha hai
6) app.use() execute ho gaya
7) res.send() ke baad response close
8) app.get() kabhi run hi nahi hua

Output:
app.use() method called

 Dry Run Example â€“ Case 2 (Order changed)

import express from "express";
const app = express();

app.get("/address/pincode", (req, res) => {
  res.send("app.get() method called");
});

app.use("/about/address", (req, res) => {
  res.send("app.use() method called");
});

Request:
GET /address/pincode

Execution flow:
1) Express top se route check karega
2) app.get("/address/pincode") milega
3) Method = GET (match)
4) Path = /address/pincode (exact match)
5) Dono condition match ho gayi
6) app.get() execute ho gaya
7) res.send() ke baad response close
8) app.use() check hi nahi hua

Output:
app.get() method called

-- Final One-Line Conclusion (Interview + GitHub)

app.use() prefix-based matching karta hai aur HTTP method se independent hota hai,
jabki app.get()/post()/put()/delete() exact path aur exact HTTP method par kaam karte hain.
Express routes ko top-to-bottom evaluate karta hai.
*/
